Ideally, these files would be generated by the build.
However, that requires the build to download the minecraft JAR file and then execute it.
Which, while feasible, is too much effort for right now.

So, instead, the file datagen-version.txt contains the version of Minecraft used to generate
the current copies of the file.  The build will compare this version and fail when it does not
match the minecraft version target of the build.  The developer can then regenerate the data
or simply update the version number file if the file versions are satisfactory as-is.

Here is the general form of the command used with the server JAR file to produce the data:

    java -DbundlerMainClass="net.minecraft.data.Main" -jar minecraft.jar --server
